<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; MALCOLM AND HAJJ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SALAM AL-MARAYATI, director of the Muslim Public Affairs Council in Los 
Angeles, commented on the anniversary of the birth of Malcolm X and the season 
of Hajj, the pilgrimage of Muslims to Mecca, against a backdrop of the 40th 
anniversary of the Supreme Court decision against school segregation in 
America. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 During Hajj, Malcolm realized the need for human understanding to overcome his 
personal problems about racism. The absence of racial images in Islam deters 
supremacy and facilitates pluralism within society.Malcolm manifested this 
doctrine, and his example for society went even deeper. He eliminated the inner 
oppressor to enable himself to fight the oppressors of the world. His 
introspection and intellectual honesty were the main driving forces for his 
evolution from a community activist to a world leader. 
</P>
<P>
 President Clinton has called for racial equality this week and said that we 
could no longer be two nations, separate and unequal. We can all enrich our 
human understanding by accepting Malcolm X as a living example of the Koranic 
principle: "God created you all out of a male and a female, and has made you 
into different nations and tribes, not to despise one another, but to learn 
from one another." 
</P>
</TEXT>
