<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHERE THE HERBS ARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the April 7 Letters section, Walter Houk asks for epazote sources. I grow 
it in my back-yard garden -- it will self-seed in this climate.Seeds are 
available from Plants of the Southwest (Aqua Fria, Route 6, Box 11 A, Santa Fe, 
N.M. 87505) and Nichols Garden Nursery (Old Pacific North, Albany, Ore. 97321). 
It is a trouble-free plant that could probably be grown in planters as well as 
in the garden. 
</P>
<P>
 -- SHARON L. JOHNSON 
</P>
<P>
 Eagle Rock 
</P>
<P>
 Epazote is difficult to find, but well worth the effort. Dried epazote is sold 
at El Mercado market, 3425 East 1st St., Los Angeles, (213) 269-2953. It is 
also available via mail order from Southwest Gourmet Gallery, Sinagua Plaza, 
Suite D, 320 N. Highway 89A, Sedona, Ariz. 86336, (602) 282-2682 or (800) 
888-3484. 
</P>
<P>
 -- CARMEN HILLEBREW 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
