<HEADLINE>
<P>
MONTANA GOVERNOR DELIVERS GRADUATION ADDRESS -- FOR ONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It wasn't easy, but Gov. Marc Racicot delivered his commencement address as 
promised. And the graduating class of one appreciated what the governor went 
through to get there. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just wanted someone special to come to my graduation," said 14-year-old 
Cory Rieber, an eighth-grader at Reichle School. "He was pretty much my only 
choice." 
</P>
<P>
 Bad weather forced Racicot to make the 100-mile trip from Helena by car 
instead of plane. The last stretch took him over a muddy country road, past men 
in fields setting irrigation pipes, a feedlot full of yearling cattle and a 
yard filled with last year's hay crop. 
</P>
<P>
 Glen is a ranching community in southwestern Montana. About 60 people -- and 
all 17 students at the two-room school -- turned out to hear the governor on 
Tuesday. The school has children in kindergarten through eighth grade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
