<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFFICIALS GET GUN TIED TO HUEY LONG SLAYING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The gun some people believe was used to kill Huey Long was turned over 
Wednesday to the Louisiana State Police, which lost possession of it more than 
half a century ago. 
</P>
<P>
 For the last three years, the Browning 7.65-millimeter automatic has been the 
subject of a court fight over its ownership. 
</P>
<P>
 Most historians believe that Dr. Carl A. Weiss pulled the gun and shot Long in 
the state Capitol on Sept. 8, 1935. Long's bodyguards killed Weiss. 
</P>
<P>
 Some historians claim Long was killed by a bodyguard's errant shot. 
</P>
<P>
 The alleged assassin's son, Carl A. Weiss Jr., claimed ownership of the gun 
and eventually won. His attorney gave the gun to state police Wednesday as a 
donation valued for tax purposes at $265,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
