<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; ANTI-GANG SEMINAR TARGETS MIGRANT WORKERS' 
CHILDREN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK SABBATINI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Migrant workers will be given advice on how to keep their children from 
getting involved in gang activities at a free conference Saturday at Castaic 
Elementary School. 
</P>
<P>
 The Spanish-language seminar will focus on warning signs parents should watch 
for and how to reduce tensions among cultures, said Carol Ramnarine, a program 
specialist with the Los Angeles County Office of Education.  
</P>
<P>
 She said gang infiltration among children of migrant parents in the Santa 
Clarita Valley is not rampant, but many parents requested the topic. 
</P>
<P>
 "Over a period of about three years, we've had at least nine students arrested 
for gang activities," she said. "They're not serious activities, but there's 
enough that we want to say, 'Let's not let this get out of hand.' " 
</P>
<P>
 Ramnarine estimated there are about 185 children of migrant workers in the 
Santa Clarita Valley, down from about 400 several years ago. She said many of 
the area's produce fields were shut down in 1989 by their owner, Boskovich 
Farms, causing much of the decline in the migrant population. 
</P>
<P>
 A mural created by about 25 students in grades six through 12 also will be 
unveiled at the conference before it is displayed at educational conferences 
around the country, Ramnarine said. She said the mural, titled "Harvest of 
Hope," consists of three 36-by-48-inch panels with St. Guadalupe at the center. 
</P>
<P>
 "She is kind of similar to the Virgin Mary," she added. "She bridges the Aztec 
culture to Catholicism." 
</P>
<P>
 The mural features other images such as an Aztec sun calendar, a man 
representing the Mexican revolution and the border between the United States 
and Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
 The meeting is the second annual Migrant Parent Conference sponsored by the 
county Office of Education, the city of Santa Clarita and local community 
groups. Ramnarine said the conference is targeted at migrant parents, but all 
Latinos are welcome to attend. 
</P>
<P>
 Registration begins at 9 a.m. and the discussions will run from 10 a.m. to 
noon. Castaic Elementary School is at 31700 Ridge Route Road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
