<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: PLACENTIA; CITY OKS 19-CENT HIKE IN TRASH RATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved a 19-cent increase in the monthly trash fee for 
city residents, and officials warned residents to expect future hikes as the 
cost of dumping trash at county landfills rises. 
</P>
<P>
 Though the county is not expected to increase landfill costs this year, City 
Administrator Robert D'Amato said he expects future fee hikes. 
</P>
<P>
 "The county is not going to lose money on landfill operations," D'Amato said. 
"The cost is going to go up and up." 
</P>
<P>
 The 1.5% increase, to $12.79 a month, includes a 5-cent addition for trash 
collection, a 13-cent increase for recycling collection and a 1-cent increase 
in the bulky item pickup charge. 
</P>
<P>
 The new rate, which goes into effect July 1, is the sixth lowest of the 13 
cities in the county with comparable service, according to a city staff report. 
</P>
<P>
 Commercial trash rates will also increase between 1.6% and 3.1% a month, 
depending on the type of trash container. 
</P>
<P>
 Several residents said the price increase proves that Taormina Industries is 
an inefficient trash hauler and that the city should hire a new company. 
</P>
<P>
 "If they have to have two raises in one year, maybe we're with the wrong 
contractor," said Sharon Burnside during a public hearing on the proposed 
increase. DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</TEXT>
