<HEADLINE>
<P>
D-DAY ANNIVERSARY ALL OVER THE TUBE; TELEVISION: SHOWS ABOUT THE ALLIED LANDING 
IN FRANCE WILL RUN ON THE NETWORKS AS WELL AS CABLE -- AND THERE WILL BE PLENTY 
TO PICK AMONG. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Programs about D-day will be exploding like a full-scale aerial attack in the 
coming weeks as television pays tribute to the 50th anniversary of the invasion 
that decisively changed the momentum of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
 There will be extensive coverage of events on the actual anniversary, June 6, 
but that will be the culmination of media focus. Here's a guide to some of 
what's on tap before then: 
</P>
<P>
 * PBS' "The American Experience" series devotes an hour on May 25 to "D-Day," 
a documentary by Charles Guggenheim. 
</P>
<P>
 * Retired Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf and Dan Rather will host a two-hour "CBS 
Reports" on May 26, visiting the Normandy beaches where the Allied invasion of 
Europe began and talking with many of the Americans who fought there and with 
the sons of the commanding generals that day. 
</P>
<P>
 * Charles Durning, a participant in the assault on Omaha Beach, narrates 
"Normandy: The Great Crusade," a two-hour documentary on the Discovery Channel 
May 30. 
</P>
<P>
 * George Stevens Jr. has put together footage shot by his father's military 
film unit for "George Stevens: D-Day to Berlin," airing May 31 on the Disney 
Channel. 
</P>
<P>
 * Peter Jennings will anchor a 90-minute edition of "Turning Point" on ABC 
June 1 that will interview veterans on both sides of the battle to reconstruct 
the planning and strategies that went into the attack. 
</P>
<P>
 * Charles Osgood will anchor "CBS News Sunday Morning" from Normandy on June 
5, devoting the entire program to D-day. David Brinkley will do the same that 
day for his ABC show, "This Week With David Brinkley." 
</P>
<P>
 * "Eye on History: D-Day," produced by Lou Reda Productions with the 
cooperation of the U.S. Naval Institute, had its first A&E outing May 18 and 
repeats June 5 at 1 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * CNN has scheduled an hourlong documentary, "D-Day: The Great Crusade," for 
June 5, with Judy Woodruff anchoring and Lou Waters reporting. It features 
interviews with men on the front lines and the women working at home in the 
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
